WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.440
My name's Charlotte Wickham and I'm a developer educator on the Quarto team at Posit.

00:00:11.440 --> 00:00:16.160
It's been a little over a year since we introduced Quarto and the team has been working really

00:00:16.160 --> 00:00:19.200
hard on some new features.

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:23.520
I know you can get so caught up actually working with your tools that it's hard to keep up

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:26.000
with the changes in those tools.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:31.480
So think about this as your annual holiday letter from a fond but far away friend, updating

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:34.040
you on the highlights of the year.

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:38.799
I'll focus on the things that I think are most useful to you as an author of Quarto

00:00:38.799 --> 00:00:41.919
documents, grouped into three categories.

00:00:41.919 --> 00:00:47.160
Content, these are things you can add to any Quarto document that enhance or add content

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:49.040
to that document.

00:00:49.040 --> 00:00:53.680
Projects, a couple of features that make it easier to work with collections of Quarto

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:55.160
documents.

00:00:55.160 --> 00:01:01.680
And tools, these are enhancements to the tools you might use to author Quarto documents.

00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:06.959
Before we jump in, let me give you a little context on Quarto versions.

00:01:06.959 --> 00:01:12.160
Quarto 1.0 was the version when Quarto was released last year.

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:17.839
Quarto 1.1 and 1.2 were released before the end of the year and Quarto 1.3 was released

00:01:17.839 --> 00:01:21.080
in April this year, 2023.

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:25.360
Quarto 1.3 is the current release, that means it's the one you'll find when you head to

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:32.000
our downloads page on quarto.org and it's the version that the documentation describes.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.320
We do release updates to the current release but those updates are somewhat infrequent.

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:43.320
Some of the features I'll describe today are coming in Quarto 1.4 and if you want to try

00:01:43.320 --> 00:01:47.320
them out, you'll need to download what we call the pre-release.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:53.080
The pre-release is a snapshot of the main branch of Git repo and as such, it's updated

00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:54.080
really frequently.

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:58.000
So, if you're going to sit down and do something with the pre-release, you want to make sure

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:02.400
you grab the latest version from quarto.org.

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:07.639
If you aren't sure which version of Quarto you have, you can use the version option to

00:02:07.639 --> 00:02:09.759
Quarto on the command line.

00:02:09.759 --> 00:02:15.679
Okay, let's jump in to some new content features.

00:02:15.679 --> 00:02:20.399
The first feature I want to show you is the embed shortcode.

00:02:20.399 --> 00:02:25.800
Imagine you've got a Quarto document and you've imported some data, done some processing,

00:02:25.800 --> 00:02:30.080
done some exploration and you've landed at a visualization that you really want to include

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:32.639
in another document.

00:02:32.639 --> 00:02:36.320
I'll call this document with all the code that gets to the visualization, the source

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:37.940
document.

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:42.940
What you want to end up with is another document, I'll call it the destination, with just this

00:02:42.979 --> 00:02:46.100
visualization in it.

00:02:46.100 --> 00:02:50.059
The embed shortcode lets you do that with one line.

00:02:50.059 --> 00:02:51.059
Let's see.

00:02:51.059 --> 00:02:57.100
Here's that source document and the code chunk that generates the visualization.

00:02:57.100 --> 00:03:01.699
We'll need a way to identify the cell, so let's add a label.

00:03:01.699 --> 00:03:05.020
I'll call it fig-scatter.

00:03:05.020 --> 00:03:08.660
Then in the destination document, I'll use the shortcode.

00:03:08.660 --> 00:03:15.979
The embed shortcode requires a path to the source file, followed by a cell identifier.

00:03:15.979 --> 00:03:17.979
That's it.

00:03:17.979 --> 00:03:23.100
The cell options come from the source document, so if you want to add a caption, you'll need

00:03:23.100 --> 00:03:26.660
to do that in the source document.

00:03:26.660 --> 00:03:31.380
When rendered, the output from that source document will be included in the destination

00:03:31.380 --> 00:03:32.380
document.

00:03:32.820 --> 00:03:39.419
In HTML formats, you also get a link back to a rendered version of that source document.

00:03:39.419 --> 00:03:44.179
The embed shortcode was introduced in Corto 1.3, but only when the source was a Jupyter

00:03:44.179 --> 00:03:45.179
notebook.

00:03:45.179 --> 00:03:54.300
In Corto 1.4, you'll be able to do embeds from QMD documents too.

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:59.179
Corto 1.4 is bringing some big changes to cross-references.

00:03:59.179 --> 00:04:04.860
In particular, you'll be able to make almost anything a cross-referenceable element.

00:04:04.860 --> 00:04:10.919
All the current cross-reference syntax will still work, but Corto 1.4 adds some new syntax

00:04:10.919 --> 00:04:13.380
that's more flexible.

00:04:13.380 --> 00:04:19.179
To define a cross-referenceable element, you'll need to create a div with an ID that has a

00:04:19.179 --> 00:04:24.179
prefix that Corto recognizes as a cross-reference.

00:04:24.179 --> 00:04:30.779
So for instance, here, the triple colons indicate the div, followed by an ID starting

00:04:30.779 --> 00:04:35.859
with fig, that lets Corto know that this is a figure cross-reference.

00:04:35.859 --> 00:04:40.540
Then comes the content for this element, and then the final line will be interpreted as

00:04:40.540 --> 00:04:42.500
the caption.

00:04:42.500 --> 00:04:47.820
Then I can refer back to this element using the usual syntax, an at symbol followed by

00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:50.600
the ID of the element.

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:56.200
When rendered, Corto adds figure, along with a counter, and generates the text and link

00:04:56.200 --> 00:05:00.200
wherever I refer back to this element.

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:04.200
With this new syntax, I can put almost anything inside this div.

00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:09.079
I could put a code cell inside and call it a figure, or I could put an image inside,

00:05:09.079 --> 00:05:14.440
and by changing the prefix to tbl, call it a table.

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:18.660
The other new thing you'll be able to do is define custom types of cross-reference in

00:05:18.660 --> 00:05:21.059
your YAML.

00:05:21.059 --> 00:05:25.980
The keynames here are still a work in progress, but essentially, you decide what the prefix

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:31.459
will be that will identify this as a cross-reference in the div ID, and the labels used in the

00:05:31.459 --> 00:05:35.739
caption, and for the in-text references.

00:05:35.739 --> 00:05:39.579
Here I'm defining one that will represent diagrams.

00:05:39.579 --> 00:05:45.739
Then you can switch to this new type of cross-reference, and now you have control over the text used

00:05:45.739 --> 00:05:49.179
to represent this reference.

00:05:49.179 --> 00:05:54.820
Each type of cross-reference maintains its own counter, so defining a new type of cross-reference

00:05:54.820 --> 00:06:01.500
also gives you a way to restart a counter.

00:06:01.500 --> 00:06:06.899
This next feature is specific to the Jupyter engine, and it adds a feature that Nitar users

00:06:06.899 --> 00:06:12.500
have had for a long time, an easy way to get computed values inline.

00:06:12.579 --> 00:06:17.779
So for example, imagine you had a document with a Python code cell that defined the variable

00:06:17.779 --> 00:06:24.019
radius, and what you want in your output is a sentence that refers to the value in that

00:06:24.019 --> 00:06:25.779
variable.

00:06:25.779 --> 00:06:30.059
It used to be that you'd need a code cell, and inside that code cell, you would have

00:06:30.059 --> 00:06:37.980
to generate the markdown for that entire sentence, and then feed it into the markdown function.

00:06:38.059 --> 00:06:45.140
Auto 1.4 introduces a new syntax for inline execution, single backticks, followed by Python

00:06:45.140 --> 00:06:49.339
and curly braces, followed by the code to be executed.

00:06:49.339 --> 00:06:53.660
In this case, we're just grabbing the variable itself.

00:06:53.660 --> 00:06:58.339
Or if you happen to use the Julia Jupyter kernel, you could swap this out for a Julia

00:06:58.339 --> 00:07:03.459
example as well.

00:07:03.459 --> 00:07:08.059
The final content features I want to talk about are really useful if you tend to write

00:07:08.059 --> 00:07:13.220
about code, and you want to add additional context for your readers.

00:07:13.220 --> 00:07:17.940
For example, imagine seeing this code in a rendered document.

00:07:17.940 --> 00:07:22.859
It happens to be YAML, and it was produced with this markdown in its source.

00:07:22.859 --> 00:07:27.140
I think the first piece of context people need when they're looking at code is where

00:07:27.140 --> 00:07:29.420
this code is.

00:07:29.420 --> 00:07:36.940
In this case, this is code you'd find in the __corto.yaml file in a Corto project.

00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:42.140
You can add that by adding the filename attribute to the code cell, which adds a header to the

00:07:42.140 --> 00:07:44.500
code cell in the rendered output.

00:07:44.500 --> 00:07:49.660
Here, the code lives in an actual file, but the filename attribute doesn't have to be

00:07:49.660 --> 00:07:51.019
a filename.

00:07:51.019 --> 00:07:57.059
For instance, you might say, this code is written in the terminal, or this code is written

00:07:57.059 --> 00:08:00.100
on the R console.

00:08:00.100 --> 00:08:04.579
The other feature for adding context to code is code annotation.

00:08:04.579 --> 00:08:08.940
Code annotation lets you add comments about specific lines of code.

00:08:08.940 --> 00:08:14.859
For HTML output, I really like the hover setting, where the annotation is only revealed on hover

00:08:14.859 --> 00:08:18.500
so that it doesn't distract from the code.

00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:23.859
Adding code annotation is a matter of adding specially formatted comments to the code itself,

00:08:23.859 --> 00:08:28.140
along with an ordered list directly following the code.

00:08:28.140 --> 00:08:33.500
Now, switching to projects.

00:08:33.500 --> 00:08:38.260
Because they involve many files, Corto projects can sometimes be a little bit more complicated

00:08:38.260 --> 00:08:40.940
to get started.

00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:46.859
Create is a Corto command introduced in 1.2 that makes it really easy to produce a minimal

00:08:46.859 --> 00:08:48.979
working project.

00:08:48.979 --> 00:08:53.739
Here I am on the terminal running corto create.

00:08:53.739 --> 00:08:59.419
This then runs through an interactive prompt, where I can select I want to create a project

00:08:59.419 --> 00:09:04.820
of type website in the directory test-website.

00:09:04.820 --> 00:09:11.059
Corto then creates that directory and populates it with a minimal working set of files.

00:09:11.059 --> 00:09:16.460
This works in any terminal, but because I use the RStudio terminal, Corto will create

00:09:16.460 --> 00:09:19.979
an RStudio project file and open up that project for me.

00:09:20.539 --> 00:09:23.979
Then I might build it just to see what I've got.

00:09:23.979 --> 00:09:28.419
I love using the interactive prompt, but you can also specify all those options as part

00:09:28.419 --> 00:09:30.659
of the command.

00:09:30.659 --> 00:09:35.739
This is a really handy way to build small reproducible examples of projects, or to get

00:09:35.739 --> 00:09:41.500
started with a project type that's new to you.

00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:47.179
The other project feature I want to show you are what's called project profiles.

00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:52.219
Imagine you've got a project where you need variations of basically the same content,

00:09:52.219 --> 00:09:55.380
but for different audiences or different venues.

00:09:55.380 --> 00:10:01.099
So for example, maybe you want a version of a report to share with external stakeholders,

00:10:01.099 --> 00:10:06.539
and another version for internal use that has a little bit more detail.

00:10:06.539 --> 00:10:13.020
Your project might start like this, a corto file report.qmd, where I've just got a placeholder

00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:16.340
for some content that everyone might see.

00:10:16.340 --> 00:10:21.419
Get underscore corto dot yaml, with some project level information, like the project

00:10:21.419 --> 00:10:29.340
title, and a location for the rendered output to go, in this case a folder called external.

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:38.219
So if I was to render this project, I'd get this report dot html in the folder external.

00:10:38.219 --> 00:10:42.020
This represents rendering without a profile activated.

00:10:42.020 --> 00:10:48.320
To add a profile, you add another corto configuration file, but with an extra suffix.

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:54.099
I'm going to call mine underscore corto dash internal dot yaml.

00:10:54.099 --> 00:11:00.099
To activate the profile, you can add the profile option to the render command.

00:11:00.099 --> 00:11:06.700
So here I'm running corto render, with profile set to internal.

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:11.140
When activated, the options in the profile configuration file are merged with those in

00:11:11.140 --> 00:11:13.900
the default configuration file.

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:18.820
I'm going to add a different output directory to my internal profile.

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:20.539
Let me say internal.

00:11:20.539 --> 00:11:26.419
Then, when I render with this profile activated, I get this report dot html in the internal

00:11:26.419 --> 00:11:27.419
folder.

00:11:27.419 --> 00:11:33.760
Not very exciting yet, but I can use this profile to start making changes that distinguish

00:11:33.760 --> 00:11:37.820
the internal output from my default output.

00:11:37.820 --> 00:11:45.619
So just to visually make a distinction, I could add a theme to my internal profile.

00:11:45.619 --> 00:11:53.179
In addition to having a profile apply different options, you can also use it to control content.

00:11:53.179 --> 00:11:55.820
Let's take another look at report dot qmd.

00:11:55.820 --> 00:12:01.140
I'm going to add some content that I want only visible in the internal report.

00:12:01.140 --> 00:12:05.640
To have it show up only when the internal profile is activated, I can put it inside

00:12:05.640 --> 00:12:15.239
a div and add the content visible class with the when profile attribute set to internal.

00:12:15.239 --> 00:12:20.719
Now if I render both with and without the internal profile activated, I get these two

00:12:20.719 --> 00:12:22.599
versions.

00:12:22.599 --> 00:12:27.840
Report dot html in the external folder has only one section, and report dot html in the

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:34.320
internal folder has two.

00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:40.200
The biggest changes in authoring tools are to our extensions for Visual Studio Code and

00:12:40.200 --> 00:12:41.880
JupyterLab.

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:48.200
The Visual Studio Code extension now has a visual editor, just like RStudio.

00:12:48.200 --> 00:12:52.820
When you enter the visual editor, you get a what-you-see-is-what-you-get editing experience

00:12:52.820 --> 00:12:55.200
for your Koto documents.

00:12:55.200 --> 00:12:59.799
For example, rather than seeing markdown syntax, you see formatted text.

00:12:59.799 --> 00:13:05.039
One of the nicest features of the visual editor is the insert anything tool.

00:13:05.039 --> 00:13:09.359
Simply type a forward slash, and you'll get a dropdown of all the content types you might

00:13:09.359 --> 00:13:11.280
insert.

00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:14.099
A nice example is insert table.

00:13:14.099 --> 00:13:18.580
And if you only need one reason to use the visual editor, it should be for editing tables

00:13:18.580 --> 00:13:24.200
without having to worry about markdown syntax.

00:13:24.200 --> 00:13:28.299
Another nice feature in the Visual Studio Code extension is completion for citations

00:13:28.299 --> 00:13:30.260
and cross-references.

00:13:30.260 --> 00:13:34.859
Simply type the at symbol, and you'll see completions for cross-referenceable items

00:13:34.859 --> 00:13:44.619
like figures, tables, or sections, as well as citations from your bibliography file.

00:13:44.619 --> 00:13:48.460
There is now also a JupyterLab Koto extension.

00:13:48.460 --> 00:13:53.179
This extension interprets the Koto markdown in your file, and gives you a more realistic

00:13:53.340 --> 00:13:58.940
preview of that document from within the editor.

00:13:58.940 --> 00:14:01.780
That's it for the new features I wanted to show you.

00:14:01.780 --> 00:14:06.059
There are a couple of other big features coming in Koto 1.4 that I haven't talked about,

00:14:06.059 --> 00:14:09.820
because you can hear about them in other PositConf talks.

00:14:09.820 --> 00:14:15.940
That's manuscript projects for scholarly writing, and typist support as an alternative

00:14:15.940 --> 00:14:20.179
to LaTeX for PDF output.

00:14:20.179 --> 00:14:24.179
You might be wondering how you can keep up with changes to Koto.

00:14:24.179 --> 00:14:30.219
The most definitive list for the changes in each Koto release is the changelog, and you

00:14:30.219 --> 00:14:33.780
can find that on the download page on koto.org.

00:14:33.780 --> 00:14:38.780
You can also find them in the news folder on our GitHub repo.

00:14:38.780 --> 00:14:43.179
We also like to blog about some of the highlights of each release, so you might want to follow

00:14:43.179 --> 00:14:46.039
the Koto blog as well.

00:14:46.039 --> 00:14:50.919
The best place to ask questions about new or old features is on the discussion board

00:14:50.919 --> 00:14:53.119
on our GitHub repo.

00:14:53.119 --> 00:14:57.080
And if there's something new in Koto you'd like to see, there's a feature request category

00:14:57.080 --> 00:15:00.760
there too.

00:15:00.760 --> 00:15:04.440
Thanks for listening, and I hope you've seen something that you're eager to try out.

