00:16:16.320 --> 00:16:21.840
Charlotte, why is the syntax for inline code for Python and Julia slightly different than

00:16:21.840 --> 00:16:22.840
R?

00:16:22.840 --> 00:16:27.679
That's a good question.

00:16:27.679 --> 00:16:31.320
And somebody more knowledgeable than I will know exactly why, but as far as I know, it's

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:36.760
sort of a limitation of the Jupyter engine.

00:16:36.760 --> 00:16:39.520
And I know it can be a little bit jarring, because if you're used to R, you're used to

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:45.159
just the backtick and then a sort of bare letter R. The good news is that we're actually

00:16:45.159 --> 00:16:51.559
also including that new style syntax for R for the Knitter engine, so that, for instance,

00:16:51.559 --> 00:16:54.760
if you're teaching this, there's sort of only one syntax you'll need to teach.

00:16:54.760 --> 00:17:00.599
So starting in Koto 1.4, you'll also be able to, in Knitter, say single backtick and then

00:17:00.599 --> 00:17:05.520
R in those curly braces, that same syntax will work for you.

00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:11.199
That's really fun to watch Charlotte explain, and Carlos go like, yes, yes, yes, yes, yes.

00:17:11.199 --> 00:17:14.359
It's excellent.

00:17:14.359 --> 00:17:19.599
Multicolumn documents, specifically multicolumn PDFs, is that possible in Quarter?

00:17:19.599 --> 00:17:21.479
Yeah, totally possible.

00:17:21.479 --> 00:17:24.680
That's possible now.

00:17:24.680 --> 00:17:30.359
It is one of the areas where our documentation is perhaps a little bit hard to find, but

00:17:30.359 --> 00:17:37.079
you want to hunt around on the website for the layout attribute.

00:17:37.079 --> 00:17:42.400
Most of our examples show that with HTML, so it's really easy to sort of put elements

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:47.439
in columns with that, but that also works in PDF.

00:17:47.439 --> 00:17:51.560
That will, that's generally something you might do on an element kind of basis, like

00:17:51.560 --> 00:17:57.439
you've got a couple of figures in a table that you want to lay out in multiple columns.

00:17:57.520 --> 00:18:04.839
You can also, of course, use any of the LaTeX or, coming soon, typist ways of doing that

00:18:04.839 --> 00:18:06.800
at a document level.

